5|$|Renamed in 1997 to <b>Oldham</b> Roughyeds, <b>Oldham</b> Rugby League Club has {{received}} several club honours during its history, winning the Rugby Football League Championship five times and Challenge Cup three times. They played at Watersheddings {{for years before}} joining <b>Oldham</b> Athletic at Boundary Park until 2010 when they moved to <b>Oldham</b> Borough's previous ground, Whitebank Stadium. <b>Oldham</b> has league cricket teams {{with a number of}} semi-professional league clubs including <b>Oldham</b> CC, and Werneth CC in the Central Lancashire League.|$|E
5|$|University Campus <b>Oldham</b> is a centre {{for higher}} {{education}} and a sister campus of the University of Huddersfield. It was opened in May 2005 by actor Patrick Stewart, the centre's Chancellor. The University Campus <b>Oldham</b> presented actress Shobna Gulati and artist, Brian Clarke (both born in <b>Oldham)</b> with an Honorary Doctorate of Letters at the Graduation Ceremony of November 2006, for their achievements and contributions to <b>Oldham</b> and its community.|$|E
5|$|Beharall {{started his}} {{football}} playing career for Newcastle United in 1996 and graduated {{to the first}} team in 1998. While at St James' Park he had loan spells at Grimsby Town and <b>Oldham</b> Athletic in 2001 and 2002 before joining <b>Oldham</b> for a fee of £150,000 in March 2002. He left <b>Oldham</b> in February 2005 to join Carlisle United on a free transfer {{and a year later}} in February 2006 Beharall joined Stockport County before retiring due to a knee injury three months later.|$|E
